com.googlecode.biscotti.collect

Class RankList<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractList<E>
        • com.googlecode.biscotti.collect.RankList<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of elements maintained by this list
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.List<E>

    public final class RankList<E>
extends java.util.AbstractList<E>
implements java.util.List<E>, java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable
    A List optimized for efficient random access insertion and removal operations. Implements all optional list operations, and permits all elements, including null.

    The iterators obtained from the iterator() and listIterator() methods are fail-fast. Attempts to modify the elements in this list at any time after an iterator is created, in any way except through the iterator's own remove method, will result in a ConcurrentModificationException.

    This list is not thread-safe. If multiple threads modify this list concurrently it must be synchronized externally.

    This class implements an array-based Skip List modified to provide logarithmic running time for linear list operations (e.g. insert an element at the ith index). Linear list operations are sometimes referred to as rank operations.

    Invented by Bill Pugh in 1990, A Skip List is a probabilistic data structure for maintaining items in sorted order. Strictly speaking it is impossible to make any hard guarantees regarding the worst-case performance of this class. Practical performance is expected to be logarithmic with an extremely high degree of probability as the list grows.

    The following table summarizes the performance of this class compared to an ArrayList and a LinkedList (where n is the size of the list and m is the size of the specified collection):

    Method Running Time
    RankList
    (expected)    		 ArrayList
    (amortized)    		 LinkedList
    (worst-case)
    addAll(Collection) O(m log n) O(m)
    containsAll(Collection) O(m * n)
    removeAll(Collection)
    retainAll(Collection)
    add(E) O(log n) O(1) O(1)
    get(int)
    		O(n)
    set(int, E)
    add(int, E)
    		 O(n)
    remove(int)
    listIterator(int)
    Iterator.remove() O(1)
    ListIterator.remove()
    ListIterator.add(E)
    ListIterator.set(E) O(1)
    clear()
    contains(Object)
    indexOf(Object)
    lastIndexOf(Object)
    remove(Object)     		O(n)

    The subList view exhibits identical time complexity, with the exception of the clear() operation which runs in linear time proportional to the size of the view.

        public java.util.Iterator<E> iterator()
        Description copied from class: java.util.AbstractList
        Returns an iterator over the elements in this list in proper sequence.

        This implementation returns a straightforward implementation of the iterator interface, relying on the backing list's size(), get(int), and remove(int) methods.

        Note that the iterator returned by this method will throw an UnsupportedOperationException in response to its remove method unless the list's remove(int) method is overridden.

      • lastIndexOf

        public int lastIndexOf(java.lang.Object o)
        Description copied from class: java.util.AbstractList
        Returns the index of the last occurrence of the specified element in this list, or -1 if this list does not contain the element. More formally, returns the highest index i such that (o==null ? get(i)==null : o.equals(get(i))), or -1 if there is no such index.

        This implementation first gets a list iterator that points to the end of the list (with listIterator(size())). Then, it iterates backwards over the list until the specified element is found, or the beginning of the list is reached.

      • listIterator

        public java.util.ListIterator<E> listIterator(int index)
        Description copied from class: java.util.AbstractList
        Returns a list iterator over the elements in this list (in proper sequence), starting at the specified position in the list. The specified index indicates the first element that would be returned by an initial call to next. An initial call to previous would return the element with the specified index minus one.

        This implementation returns a straightforward implementation of the ListIterator interface that extends the implementation of the Iterator interface returned by the iterator() method. The ListIterator implementation relies on the backing list's get(int), set(int, E), add(int, E) and remove(int) methods.

        Note that the list iterator returned by this implementation will throw an UnsupportedOperationException in response to its remove, set and add methods unless the list's remove(int), set(int, E), and add(int, E) methods are overridden.

        This implementation can be made to throw runtime exceptions in the face of concurrent modification, as described in the specification for the (protected) AbstractList.modCount field.

        Specified by:

        Overrides:
